th poems by a range of authors in the late sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, including Joseph Hall, Thomas Nashe, Tailboys Dymoke, Thomas Middleton and George Wither, to advance the thesis that Spenser was seen by his contemporaries as highly relevant to satire in Elizabethan England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature (General). 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aShakespeare 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aBedell, William.  aDymoke, Tailboys.  aHall, Joseph.  aMiddleton, Thomas.  aNashe, Thomas.  aSatire.  aSpenser, Edmund.  aWither, George.1 aHile, Rachel E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526125132zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125132zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125132/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA